margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This submission is based on TVRCC’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">strategic and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">practical involvement in rural </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">transport </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and experience of operating a community transport service in East Cleveland for the past three years.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The response focusses significantly on rural</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> residents with additional, supported travel needs – older people, people with mobility problems, and the young.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The reasons for the higher costs of rural transport are discussed.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is an emphasis on working with and within rural communities, partnersh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ip working with the local authorities, and working with volunteers.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The importance of some degree of subsidy to the success of transport ventures in rural areas, and innovative approaches, including the use of smaller vehicles and community car schemes, ar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e highlighted.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How do Government and local authorities identify demand for passenger transport in isolated communities (including rural and urban areas and island communities)?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">This question essentially requires a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">direct </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">response from local authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, they are informed to some extent by public demand and by attendees at local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">public and rural </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">transport forums where both urban and rural communities are able to highlight shortfalls in provision and seek information on how (and if) demand can be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">met. TVRCC feed information to local authority transport departments regarding public transport needs – particularly from rural areas.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">To what extent are the needs of different groups of passengers (e.g. people with disabilities, older people, young </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">people) taken into account in determining the provision of public transport to isolated communities?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">This question also requires a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">direct </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">response from local authorities.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">People with disabilities, older people and young people are not well served by publ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ic transport as the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y often have additional needs requiring fully accessible vehicles,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> assisted travel support or supervision</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Following the withdrawal of all de</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mand-responsive local authority-subsidiz</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ed ‘Dial A </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Ride’ services in the Tees Valley, the parti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cular needs of these categories of passengers are now very poorly served. In isolated communities elderly, disabled or young</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">er</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> residents often live a considerable distance from the nearest bus stop or main service route, and in many cases need assisted tra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">vel support, which is not provided by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">commercial public transport operators.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">After school transport for pupils – outside home-to-school service provision – is rarely available and often restricts students’ ability to take part in extra-curricular activitie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Some local authorities are looking to work with community transport providers to meet these needs.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What are the main challenges associated with providing better and more consistent bus and rail services to isolated communities? How can these challenges </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">be overcome?</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The main challenges almost all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">involve </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cost.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Limited</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> passenger numbers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and greater distances travelled </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">often make a regular</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> rural bus service unsustainable and the large providers quite simply work on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a formula of: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">fares + subsidy = profit. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The villages of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Braffe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ton in the Darlington area and Lazenby in Redcar &amp; Cleveland are good examples: despite being only yards from both the main roads (A172 and Redcar trunk</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Rd) the service to Lazenby </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has been withdrawn because the provider says it is on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ly averaging 40 people daily which incurs a financial loss. This in real terms means 40 people have difficulty in getting to work, s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hopping, attending appointments or</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> making social visits. In Brafferton the removal of a link to the main bus route into Darl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ington (a 0.5 mile detour) means residents have to walk along a dangerous unsuitable route </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is impossible for the elderly.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">One approach would be to encourage the major bus companies to include rural destinations in main transport corridor route planni</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ng. In some cases, this would extend journey times slightly but as the vehicle reaches more populous areas, passenger numbers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">increase, making the service as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a whole more cost effective. Our own monitoring</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of the Arriva 5 route (Whitby to Middlesbrou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">gh) clearly shows this. There can be as few as 3 or 4 passengers on board through the journey from Whitby to L</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">oftus, but then n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">umbers increase steadily as the bus gets nearer to Middlesbrough until they are almost full on arrival. The return journey follow</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s the same pattern in reverse. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">To some ex</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tent, the community itself can hold</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the key to overcoming these challenges. As an example Lazenby </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">village </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">residents are negotiating for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a community based minibus </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to provide </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a limited </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">service</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Through </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">consultation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with the community</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> they should be able to outline routes and timetables to suit the 40 passengers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f this proves successful, over time </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">they hope </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to increase patronage by making others in their community aware that the service works.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Another area where cos</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t can be addressed positively is by the community putting forward volunteer drivers to operate the service rather than paid employees and by taking charge of the day to day opera</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tion. A large initial outlay can be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> avoided by the donation of a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">surplus </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">vehic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">le by the local authority </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to groups taking the community-based transport </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">route. Other </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">possibilities include allowing use of the vehicle outside scheduled service times for hire by community groups in the same way as the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> East Cleveland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Minibus B</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rokerage ope</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rates. A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">gain this puts the community at the centre of the operation and the more they are successful at promoting the vehicle’s use, the more likely the service can be sustainable into the future.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">An awareness </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of connectivity between</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> bus and rail would als</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o help. For </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">example, there are no buses from E</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ast </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">leveland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> into Saltburn which actually</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> connect reasonably with the on-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">going train service to Darlington and be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">yond. Returning is even worse. W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hilst you can get a train into Saltburn relatively late in the e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">vening</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> buses from there into EC finish all too early. R&amp;C have gone some way to addressing this with the Link Bus service which highlights this problem </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">as it is very well patronised</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> night,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">but still leaves more outlying villages unable to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">get home beyo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nd 7pm.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">More needs to be done to create rural transport hubs. Buses that link up with rail services to enable people to get to work and education should be the norm not the exception. More feeder networks to link in with the main public transport routes an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d services should be introduced – but they will need to be subsidised.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is difficult to provide adequate cover for a large rural network left without public transport provision after recent local authority cuts. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> opinion is that, in the vast majority </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of situations, rural tr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ansport can never be fully self-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">financing and the government and the CT sector must work together with all parties to get a “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">best possible alternative”. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">his can only be achieved with active participation by communities in both plann</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing what they need/want and actual on the ground provision of services by the community for the community</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How effectively do Community Transport services address the needs of passengers in isolated communities? How could Community Transport be improved?</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Where Community Transport service provision is geared to locally identified need the lowe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r overheads of small, volunteer-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">staffed operations can provide an effective service, but not a service that is capable of filling </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the gaps left by recent public tr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ansport cuts.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> It can however mitigate isolation to some degree by providing both group and individual transport where shortfalls and lack of access prevail</span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In our opinion Community Transport will always need a deg</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ree of subsidy / grant funding </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in order to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> make a significant difference on rural routes.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">CT can be improved in many ways: Communication and partnerships between organisations providing transport services would help greatly in improving connectivity. It would assist organisations to signpost users</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to other providers when they are unable to provide a journey</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and would have cost reduction implications by reducing dead mileage and offering the ability </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for “group</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">bargaining</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">” for servicing etc.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Some easing of the current driver (D1) legislation would b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">enefit the sector by making the recruitment and retention of volun</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">teer drivers less problematic. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">his is currently under review by the gov</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ernment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and the C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ommunity </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ransport </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ssociation.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Any arrangement which makes it easier for CT’s to gain local</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> authorit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y contracts such as home to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size