></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">To what extent should passengers in isolated communities be expected to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">rely on taxis and other demand-responsive transport services?</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For many rural able bodied residents, the only suitable transport option is car ownership. For those unable to drive or unable to afford a car</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> options are very limited. The distances involved </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n East Cleveland </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">very often make an average </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">return </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">taxi journey </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">anything from 10 to 30 miles </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">wi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">th a r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">esulting charge of up to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> £30</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">his is clearly a burden on household finances and as such deters travel</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> leading to isolation. As an example, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> young person</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> who is not in education, employment or training </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">gai</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ning a job opportunity in a remote</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> urban ce</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ntre c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ould have to spend more than they would earn on a minimum wage just to get to work and back. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">olle</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ge students from outlying areas and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> elderly people who ne</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ed to shop or attend GP surgeries </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">face similar </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">problems.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In the Tees Valley t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">here are very few operational demand responsive services to call upon and public transport is either very limited or wholly unavailable. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">opinion is that rural residents should</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> not have to rely on expensive taxis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Perhaps </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">bus companies </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">could subsidise rural fares from high density urban route revenue. </span><span style="font-